task-msit_eeg.json.TaskDescription: Extended MSIT (MSIT+) is a task design to study cognitive control and conflict processing. Standard version was firstly described by Bush et al. in 2006. The extended MSIT contains four conditions: 00 (no interference, non-conflict), S0 (Simon effect), F0 (Flanker effect), and FS (double-conflict, Simon and Flanker effects combined). Three digits are displayed in the center of the screen, including two digits that are always identical and one deviant. Participants are instructed to indicate the deviant digit in each set. In each trial, the stimulus was presented for 900 ms and followed an interstimulus interval (ISI) that ranged from 800-1300 ms (in steps of 100 ms). Task duration with breaks was set to ~22 min.

task-oddball_eeg.json.TaskDescription: In this paradigm, three stimuli (rare target — þ, rare distractor — Þ, frequent standard — p) were presented in a pseudorandom order with the restriction that two rare stimuli could not appear in a row. Participants were instructed to respond to the target stimulus (press key ‘2’ on numerical keyboard with right middle finger) and inhibit responses to other stimuli. The session contained 660 stimuli, which included approximately 12% targets, 12% deviant, and 76% standard stimuli. Task duration with breaks was set to ~22 min. Each stimulus was presented for 200 ms with an 1200-1600 ms ISI.

task-rest_eeg.json.TaskDescription: The REST task is widely used to monitor spontaneous brain activity. In particular, the REST task measures an initial, task-negative state during which no task is given to the subject. REST recording lasted for 10 minutes and was performed in an eyes-open condition. A plus sign ‘+’ was displayed centrally on a dark screen for gaze fixation.

task-srt_eeg.json.TaskDescription: SRT (simple reaction time) task data can be easily compared to the results of other tasks and provides a measure of the basic capabilities of the participants. In particular, the SRT gauges participants’ ‘average’ reaction time in response to visual stimuli, which is considered the most basic measure of processing speed. A simple stimulus (‘000’) was displayed (900 ms) centrally on the screen with 700-1200 ms ISIs (in steps of 100 ms). The participant was instructed to respond with an index finger (pressing ‘2’ on a numerical keyboard) as fast as possible. On average, 129 trials were presented to each subject.

README:
## The Nencki-Symfonia EEG/ERP dataset

Description: mixed cognitive tasks ((i) an extended multi-source interference task, MSIT+; (ii) a 3-stimuli oddball task; (iii) a control, simple reaction task, SRT; and (iv) a resting-state protocol).

Please cite the following references if you use these data:

* Dzianok P, Antonova I, Wojciechowski J, Dreszer J, Kublik E. The Nencki-Symfonia electroencephalography/event-related potential dataset: Multiple cognitive tasks and resting-state data collected in a sample of healthy adults. Gigascience. 2022 Mar 7;11:giac015. doi: 10.1093/gigascience/giac015.
* Dzianok P, Antonova I, Wojciechowski J, Dreszer J, Kublik E.  (2023). The Nencki-Symfonia EEG/ERP dataset. OpenNeuro. [Dataset] doi: doi:10.18112/openneuro.ds004609.v1.0.0
